{"parentUuid":"203bdd5b-c67d-45fe-8564-5a1e4e18b476","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7ac81ca118e1dc58","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015wuxpB9HKwNd6tJXRPX5s6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_014weBmMb6LZRLes1LkGhHFw","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Memory benchmark memorization vs generalization","subagent_type":"general-purpose","prompt":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Memorization vs. generalization in memory/agent benchmarks. How do LoCoMo, LongMemEval, Letta memory benchmarks, and Mem0 avoid measuring trivial answer-lookup / recall? What corpus-design rules make a memory benchmark test TRANSFER (a stored lesson helps on NEW but related tasks) rather than recall of a stored answer? Look for: train/test separation by task vs by answer, held-out variants, paraphrase/transfer splits, multi-hop vs single-hop questions, \"answer leakage\" critiques of these benchmarks.\n\nSearch queries to try: \"LongMemEval benchmark abstention reasoning\", \"LoCoMo benchmark criticism multi-hop\", \"Mem0 benchmark methodology answer lookup\", \"Letta memory benchmark generalization\", \"memory benchmark answer leakage contamination\", \"agent benchmark transfer vs memorization held-out\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch the 6-8 most relevant pages (arxiv papers, blog posts from Letta/Mem0, benchmark repos). Extract concrete, falsifiable claims. Return a list of findings each with: the claim, the source URL, and a one-line note on reliability. Be concrete about corpus-design rules. Return findings only as your final message."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":16152,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":16152,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":13136}}},"requestId":"req_011CcFqH4TfH6swP99Mp5bY6","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"86e95bd6-0df9-4078-b8dd-1f12b948462a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:13:38.060Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"86e95bd6-0df9-4078-b8dd-1f12b948462a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7ac81ca118e1dc58","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015wuxpB9HKwNd6tJXRPX5s6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01FoMW96vTogw9NSX7Sw7mjQ","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Sizing paired-bootstrap McNemar CI","subagent_type":"general-purpose","prompt":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Sizing a real compounding CI for a paired pass/fail (binary) benchmark. For a paired-bootstrap confidence interval OR McNemar's test on paired binary outcomes, how many tasks (and replications) are needed for the CI to EXCLUDE ZERO at a given true per-task effect size? I need rules of thumb and power-analysis guidance for:\n- Power for difference of two proportions (paired and unpaired).\n- McNemar's test sample size formula (depends on discordant pair rate / odds ratio).\n- Paired-bootstrap CI width vs n.\n- Effect-size-to-n tables: e.g., to detect a 10%, 20%, 30% absolute improvement in pass rate with 80% power.\n\nSearch queries to try: \"McNemar test sample size calculation discordant pairs\", \"paired binary outcome power analysis sample size\", \"sample size two proportions 80% power table\", \"bootstrap confidence interval sample size proportion\", \"paired bootstrap hypothesis test number of samples\", \"power analysis difference of proportions rule of thumb\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch 5-7 relevant pages (stats references, sample-size calculators, textbook excerpts). Extract concrete numbers: formulas and example n for given effect sizes. Return findings only as your final message, each with claim + source URL + reliability note. Give concrete n targets where possible."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage