{"parentUuid":"42a01d58-e1a5-4c55-9b1d-cff8e630e681","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7ac81ca118e1dc58","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015wuxpB9HKwNd6tJXRPX5s6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01YF8rvx1aZx9TfvxMSbwjjW","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Letta verifier-fed skill learning loop","subagent_type":"general-purpose","prompt":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Verifier-fed skill learning, concretely. From Letta's skill-learning work (and similar systems like Voyager, ExpeL, Agent Workflow Memory, Reflexion, \"agentic memory\"): what is the LOOP that turns a solved or failed trajectory into a reusable SKILL NOTE that helps on FUTURE related tasks (not the same task)? Specifically:\n- How is a skill extracted from a trajectory (summarization, induction)?\n- How are skills stored, retrieved, and injected into context for new tasks?\n- How does a verifier (pass/fail signal, self-critique) refine or prune skills?\n- What specifically drove Letta's reported jump from +9% to +15.7% (or similar numbers)? Find the actual Letta blog/paper on skill learning.\n\nSearch queries to try: \"Letta skill learning agent blog\", \"Letta filesystem skills self-improving agent\", \"Voyager skill library Minecraft LLM\", \"ExpeL experiential learning agent\", \"Agent Workflow Memory induction\", \"Reflexion verbal reinforcement learning\", \"agent learns reusable skills from trajectories verifier\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch 6-8 relevant pages (Letta blog, arxiv papers for Voyager/ExpeL/AWM/Reflexion). Extract concrete mechanism details and the specific performance numbers with their source. Return findings only as your final message, each with claim + source URL + reliability note."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":16152,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":16152,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":13136}}},"requestId":"req_011CcFqH4TfH6swP99Mp5bY6","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"634480db-ad33-45ed-9650-e9877755f02c","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:13:53.058Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"634480db-ad33-45ed-9650-e9877755f02c","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7ac81ca118e1dc58","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015wuxpB9HKwNd6tJXRPX5s6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01XyMQ3DuQthVxrmzmhcanMq","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Compounding layers leverage local LLM","subagent_type":"general-purpose","prompt":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Relative leverage of self-improvement / compounding layers for a small LOCAL LLM build (single 8B model, 16GB RAM, e.g. qwen3:8b via Ollama). The layers in question: (a) skills / experiential memory, (b) routing / model-cascade / navigator (picking which sub-policy or context to use), (c) distillation (fine-tuning a small student on traces). Which gives the most measurable gain per unit of engineering for a local build, and in what order should they be wired? Look for:\n- Evidence on test-time / in-context learning (skills, memory) vs fine-tuning gains for small models.\n- LLM routing / cascade effectiveness and cost-quality tradeoffs.\n- Distillation gains for small (7-8B) student models and the cost of doing it locally.\n- Any \"compound AI systems\" framing (Berkeley AI blog, DSPy) on where leverage lies.\n\nSearch queries to try: \"compound AI systems Berkeley blog\", \"LLM routing cascade cost quality\", \"in-context learning vs fine-tuning small models\", \"distillation 7B student model gains\", \"self-improving agent in-context vs weight update\", \"DSPy optimization vs fine-tuning\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch 5-7 relevant pages. Extract concrete claims and numbers about relative leverage. Return findings only as your final message, each with claim + source URL + reliability note. Be concrete about ordering recommendation for a local 8B build."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":16152,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":16152,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":13136}}},"requestId":"req_011CcFqH4TfH6swP99Mp5bY6","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"dd6e182a-7eac-44bd-9e68-286af6ef981a","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:01.076Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"dd6e182a-7eac-44bd-9e68-286af6ef981a","isSidechain":true,"agentId":"a7ac81ca118e1dc58","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-8","id":"msg_015wuxpB9HKwNd6tJXRPX5s6","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01KAywZsidEFjkq8NfCQvUaP","name":"Agent","input":{"description":"Transfer splits contamination corpus design","subagent_type":"general-purpose","prompt":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Concrete corpus/split DESIGN rules for benchmarks that measure TRANSFER and avoid contamination/answer-leakage. I want actionable design patterns I can apply to build a benchmark where \"having learned a lesson\" helps on a held-out but RELATED task, and where a system that merely memorized the answer gains nothing. Look for:\n- Compositional generalization splits (SCAN, COGS, \"systematic generalization\" — train on primitives, test on novel combinations).\n- Template / paraphrase splits where surface form differs but the underlying skill is shared.\n- Data contamination detection and decontamination practices in LLM eval.\n- \"Train on skill A's examples, test on skill A applied to new inputs\" patterns.\n- Counterfactual / perturbation evals (e.g., changing numbers/entities so the cached answer is wrong).\n\nSearch queries to try: \"compositional generalization split train test SCAN COGS\", \"benchmark data contamination decontamination LLM\", \"counterfactual evaluation perturbation reasoning\", \"template split paraphrase generalization NLP benchmark\", \"systematic generalization held-out combinations\", \"memorization vs reasoning benchmark perturbed\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch 5-7 relevant pages (arxiv, blog posts). Extract concrete, reusable design rules. Return findings only as your final message, each with claim + source URL + reliability note."},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":"tool_use","stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":16152,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":3290,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":16152},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":3290,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":16152,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":16152,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"diagnostics":{"cache_miss_reason":{"type":"tools_changed","cache_missed_input_tokens":13136}}},"requestId":"req_011CcFqH4TfH6swP99Mp5bY6","attributionAgent":"general-purpose","type":"assistant","uuid":"d157d96d-a100-4bef-8bfa-7336c1516133","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:14:08.916Z","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"42a01d58-e1a5-4c55-9b1d-cff8e630e681","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7ac81ca118e1dc58","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01FoMW96vTogw9NSX7Sw7mjQ","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive findings. Let me compile.\n\n## Findings: Sizing a paired pass/fail (binary) benchmark to exclude zero\n\n### 1. McNemar's test sample size — the right model for paired pass/fail\n\n**Claim — Only discordant pairs carry information; effective sample size = n × p_d.** For paired binary outcomes (same task run under condition A and B), concordant pairs (both pass / both fail) contribute nothing. The number of *discordant* pairs (A passes & B fails, or vice versa) drives power. Expected discordant pairs = n × p_d, where p_d = p₁₀ + p₀₁. A low discordant rate forces a large total n.\n- Source: https://metricgate.com/docs/sample-size-mcnemar-paired/ and https://powerandsamplesize.com/tutorial/how-to-calculate-sample-size-mcnemars-test/ — reliable (sample-size calculator vendors restating standard theory).\n\n**Claim — Approximate McNemar sample-size formula:**\n  n = [(z₁₋α/₂ + z₁₋β)² · (p₁₀ + p₀₁)] / (p₁₀ − p₀₁)²\nwhere p₁₀, p₀₁ are the two discordant-cell probabilities. The \"absolute improvement in pass rate\" you care about equals (p₀₁ − p₁₀), the *difference* of the two discordant cells — not p_d itself.\n- Source: https://powerandsamplesize.com/tutorial/how-to-calculate-sample-size-mcnemars-test/ — reliable.\n\n**Claim — Connor (1987) formula (used by most software):**\n  n = [z₁₋α/₂·√p_d + z₁₋β·√(p_d − (p₂₁−p₁₂)²)]² / (p₂₁ − p₁₂)²\nwith OR = p₂₁/p₁₂ as the effect; OR = 1 (no effect) needs infinite n.\n- Source: https://metricgate.com/docs/sample-size-mcnemar-paired/ — reliable (named-method restatement).\n\n### 2. Effect-size → n table for the PAIRED case (the most directly usable result)\n\n**Claim — Number of paired tasks needed (95% CI / two-sided α=0.05, 80% power), using n = z²(p₁₂+p₂₁)/d²**, where d = absolute pass-rate improvement and the discordant proportion is calibrated from 50 real within-subjects studies (median 0.22, 75th pct 0.28):\n\n| Absolute improvement d | n (p_disc = 0.22, typical) | n (p_disc = 0.28, conservative) |\n|---|---|---|\n| 10% | **343** | 436 |\n| 15% | 151 | 192 |\n| 20% | **84** | 107 |\n| 30% | **38** | 47 |\n\nWithin-subjects (paired) n is roughly 44% of the independent-groups requirement for d ≤ 30%.\n- Source: https://measuringu.com/sample-sizes-for-the-mcnemar-test/ — moderately reliable (practitioner stats site; formula and table are standard and internally consistent). Note: this formula folds the effect into d while holding p_disc fixed; it is a defensible planning approximation. The fully correct McNemar formulas above will shift these somewhat depending on how the discordant cells split, but the magnitudes are the right order.\n\n### 3. Two INDEPENDENT proportions (unpaired) — the conservative upper bound\n\n**Claim — Formula:** n per group = (z₁₋α/₂ + z₁₋β)² · [p₁(1−p₁) + p₂(1−p₂)] / (p₁ − p₂)². With α=0.05 two-sided, z₁₋α/₂ = 1.96; 80% power, z₁₋β = 0.84.\n- Source: https://select-statistics.co.uk/calculators/sample-size-calculator-two-proportions/ — reliable.\n\n**Worked numbers (per group, 80% power, α=0.05):**\n- 15% → 25% (d = 10 pts): **248 per group** (≈496 total).\n  Source: https://select-statistics.co.uk/calculators/sample-size-calculator-two-proportions/\n- 75% → 60% (d = 15 pts), 2:1 allocation: 224 + 112 = 336 total.\n  Source: https://www.medcalc.org/en/manual/sample-size-comparison-of-proportions.php\n- 5% → 35% (d = 30 pts), Fisher exact: ~32 per group.\n  Source: BU SPH / select-statistics search summary.\n\nReliability: reliable; these are textbook (Machin et al. 2009) formulas. Contrast with the paired table: 343 paired tasks vs ~248×2 = 496 observations for the same 10-pt effect — pairing roughly halves the requirement, which is the whole point of running both conditions on the *same* tasks.\n\n### 4. Paired-bootstrap CI width vs n\n\n**Claim — CI half-width shrinks as 1/√n.** Standard error and bootstrap CI width both scale ∝ 1/√n: going from n=25 to n=100 halves the margin (1/√25=0.20 → 1/√100=0.10). To halve a CI you must quadruple n. The bootstrap distribution is slightly *too narrow* by √((n−1)/n), negligible above n≈30.\n- Source: https://moderndive.com/v2/confidence-intervals.html and http://courses.washington.edu/matlab1/Lesson_6.html (via search summary) — reliable (standard asymptotics).\n- Practical translation: to make a paired-bootstrap CI on the pass-rate *difference* exclude zero, you need n large enough that ~2·(z·SE) < observed effect, i.e. the same n-targets as the McNemar table above; the bootstrap and the analytic test agree asymptotically.\n\n### 5. Number of bootstrap resamples B (this is NOT the same as n!)\n\n**Claim — B is about Monte-Carlo noise in the CI endpoints, independent of statistical power.** Recommendations:\n- B ≥ 1,000 for percentile CIs; ≥ 2,000 for BCa.\n- **B = 2,000 is \"sufficient and not greatly wasteful\"; stopping at B=1,000 inflates Monte-Carlo error by ≈√2, which can be uncomfortable at the lower CI limit.**\n- B = 10,000 is the common rule-of-thumb default for a stable distribution / stable tails.\n- Sources: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7958418/ (Efron-style analysis — high reliability), https://jepusto.com/posts/Simulating-bootstrap-CIs/ (B=1999/3999 in practice — reliable), https://statistics.tools/bootstrap-ci-calculator (≥1000, 2000+ for BCa).\n\n### Concrete recommendation for your harness\n- **Decide n (number of distinct benchmark tasks) from the PAIRED table.** For 80% power at α=0.05 two-sided to *exclude zero*: ~**38 tasks** for a 30-pt gain, ~**84** for 20 pts, ~**150** for 15 pts, ~**340** for 10 pts (assuming a ~0.22 discordant rate; raise to the 0.28 column if your conditions agree more often, which inflates n). Sub-10-pt effects get expensive fast (1/d² scaling).\n- **Decide B (bootstrap resamples) separately:** use **B = 2,000–10,000**. B does not buy power — it only sharpens the CI estimate. 2,000 minimum if you ever report a BCa interval.\n- **Use the exact-binomial McNemar (not chi-square) when discordant pairs < 25** — i.e. essentially always at small n.\n  Source: https://powerandsamplesize.com/tutorial/how-to-calculate-sample-size-mcnemars-test/\n\nKey caveat: every paired n above is driven by the *discordant* rate, not the headline pass rates. If your two conditions usually agree (small p_d), the same absolute effect needs many more tasks — measure p_d empirically on a pilot before committing to a task count."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a7a7a51fc4106ad65 (use SendMessage with to: 'a7a7a51fc4106ad65' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 28694\ntool_uses: 15\nduration_ms: 129298</usage>"}]}]},"uuid":"aeff758c-4a7c-45a0-aa09-55eb76c43100","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:55.016Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Sizing a real compounding CI for a paired pass/fail (binary) benchmark. For a paired-bootstrap confidence interval OR McNemar's test on paired binary outcomes, how many tasks (and replications) are needed for the CI to EXCLUDE ZERO at a given true per-task effect size? I need rules of thumb and power-analysis guidance for:\n- Power for difference of two proportions (paired and unpaired).\n- McNemar's test sample size formula (depends on discordant pair rate / odds ratio).\n- Paired-bootstrap CI width vs n.\n- Effect-size-to-n tables: e.g., to detect a 10%, 20%, 30% absolute improvement in pass rate with 80% power.\n\nSearch queries to try: \"McNemar test sample size calculation discordant pairs\", \"paired binary outcome power analysis sample size\", \"sample size two proportions 80% power table\", \"bootstrap confidence interval sample size proportion\", \"paired bootstrap hypothesis test number of samples\", \"power analysis difference of proportions rule of thumb\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch 5-7 relevant pages (stats references, sample-size calculators, textbook excerpts). Extract concrete numbers: formulas and example n for given effect sizes. Return findings only as your final message, each with claim + source URL + reliability note. Give concrete n targets where possible.","agentId":"a7a7a51fc4106ad65","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive findings. Let me compile.\n\n## Findings: Sizing a paired pass/fail (binary) benchmark to exclude zero\n\n### 1. McNemar's test sample size — the right model for paired pass/fail\n\n**Claim — Only discordant pairs carry information; effective sample size = n × p_d.** For paired binary outcomes (same task run under condition A and B), concordant pairs (both pass / both fail) contribute nothing. The number of *discordant* pairs (A passes & B fails, or vice versa) drives power. Expected discordant pairs = n × p_d, where p_d = p₁₀ + p₀₁. A low discordant rate forces a large total n.\n- Source: https://metricgate.com/docs/sample-size-mcnemar-paired/ and https://powerandsamplesize.com/tutorial/how-to-calculate-sample-size-mcnemars-test/ — reliable (sample-size calculator vendors restating standard theory).\n\n**Claim — Approximate McNemar sample-size formula:**\n  n = [(z₁₋α/₂ + z₁₋β)² · (p₁₀ + p₀₁)] / (p₁₀ − p₀₁)²\nwhere p₁₀, p₀₁ are the two discordant-cell probabilities. The \"absolute improvement in pass rate\" you care about equals (p₀₁ − p₁₀), the *difference* of the two discordant cells — not p_d itself.\n- Source: https://powerandsamplesize.com/tutorial/how-to-calculate-sample-size-mcnemars-test/ — reliable.\n\n**Claim — Connor (1987) formula (used by most software):**\n  n = [z₁₋α/₂·√p_d + z₁₋β·√(p_d − (p₂₁−p₁₂)²)]² / (p₂₁ − p₁₂)²\nwith OR = p₂₁/p₁₂ as the effect; OR = 1 (no effect) needs infinite n.\n- Source: https://metricgate.com/docs/sample-size-mcnemar-paired/ — reliable (named-method restatement).\n\n### 2. Effect-size → n table for the PAIRED case (the most directly usable result)\n\n**Claim — Number of paired tasks needed (95% CI / two-sided α=0.05, 80% power), using n = z²(p₁₂+p₂₁)/d²**, where d = absolute pass-rate improvement and the discordant proportion is calibrated from 50 real within-subjects studies (median 0.22, 75th pct 0.28):\n\n| Absolute improvement d | n (p_disc = 0.22, typical) | n (p_disc = 0.28, conservative) |\n|---|---|---|\n| 10% | **343** | 436 |\n| 15% | 151 | 192 |\n| 20% | **84** | 107 |\n| 30% | **38** | 47 |\n\nWithin-subjects (paired) n is roughly 44% of the independent-groups requirement for d ≤ 30%.\n- Source: https://measuringu.com/sample-sizes-for-the-mcnemar-test/ — moderately reliable (practitioner stats site; formula and table are standard and internally consistent). Note: this formula folds the effect into d while holding p_disc fixed; it is a defensible planning approximation. The fully correct McNemar formulas above will shift these somewhat depending on how the discordant cells split, but the magnitudes are the right order.\n\n### 3. Two INDEPENDENT proportions (unpaired) — the conservative upper bound\n\n**Claim — Formula:** n per group = (z₁₋α/₂ + z₁₋β)² · [p₁(1−p₁) + p₂(1−p₂)] / (p₁ − p₂)². With α=0.05 two-sided, z₁₋α/₂ = 1.96; 80% power, z₁₋β = 0.84.\n- Source: https://select-statistics.co.uk/calculators/sample-size-calculator-two-proportions/ — reliable.\n\n**Worked numbers (per group, 80% power, α=0.05):**\n- 15% → 25% (d = 10 pts): **248 per group** (≈496 total).\n  Source: https://select-statistics.co.uk/calculators/sample-size-calculator-two-proportions/\n- 75% → 60% (d = 15 pts), 2:1 allocation: 224 + 112 = 336 total.\n  Source: https://www.medcalc.org/en/manual/sample-size-comparison-of-proportions.php\n- 5% → 35% (d = 30 pts), Fisher exact: ~32 per group.\n  Source: BU SPH / select-statistics search summary.\n\nReliability: reliable; these are textbook (Machin et al. 2009) formulas. Contrast with the paired table: 343 paired tasks vs ~248×2 = 496 observations for the same 10-pt effect — pairing roughly halves the requirement, which is the whole point of running both conditions on the *same* tasks.\n\n### 4. Paired-bootstrap CI width vs n\n\n**Claim — CI half-width shrinks as 1/√n.** Standard error and bootstrap CI width both scale ∝ 1/√n: going from n=25 to n=100 halves the margin (1/√25=0.20 → 1/√100=0.10). To halve a CI you must quadruple n. The bootstrap distribution is slightly *too narrow* by √((n−1)/n), negligible above n≈30.\n- Source: https://moderndive.com/v2/confidence-intervals.html and http://courses.washington.edu/matlab1/Lesson_6.html (via search summary) — reliable (standard asymptotics).\n- Practical translation: to make a paired-bootstrap CI on the pass-rate *difference* exclude zero, you need n large enough that ~2·(z·SE) < observed effect, i.e. the same n-targets as the McNemar table above; the bootstrap and the analytic test agree asymptotically.\n\n### 5. Number of bootstrap resamples B (this is NOT the same as n!)\n\n**Claim — B is about Monte-Carlo noise in the CI endpoints, independent of statistical power.** Recommendations:\n- B ≥ 1,000 for percentile CIs; ≥ 2,000 for BCa.\n- **B = 2,000 is \"sufficient and not greatly wasteful\"; stopping at B=1,000 inflates Monte-Carlo error by ≈√2, which can be uncomfortable at the lower CI limit.**\n- B = 10,000 is the common rule-of-thumb default for a stable distribution / stable tails.\n- Sources: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC7958418/ (Efron-style analysis — high reliability), https://jepusto.com/posts/Simulating-bootstrap-CIs/ (B=1999/3999 in practice — reliable), https://statistics.tools/bootstrap-ci-calculator (≥1000, 2000+ for BCa).\n\n### Concrete recommendation for your harness\n- **Decide n (number of distinct benchmark tasks) from the PAIRED table.** For 80% power at α=0.05 two-sided to *exclude zero*: ~**38 tasks** for a 30-pt gain, ~**84** for 20 pts, ~**150** for 15 pts, ~**340** for 10 pts (assuming a ~0.22 discordant rate; raise to the 0.28 column if your conditions agree more often, which inflates n). Sub-10-pt effects get expensive fast (1/d² scaling).\n- **Decide B (bootstrap resamples) separately:** use **B = 2,000–10,000**. B does not buy power — it only sharpens the CI estimate. 2,000 minimum if you ever report a BCa interval.\n- **Use the exact-binomial McNemar (not chi-square) when discordant pairs < 25** — i.e. essentially always at small n.\n  Source: https://powerandsamplesize.com/tutorial/how-to-calculate-sample-size-mcnemars-test/\n\nKey caveat: every paired n above is driven by the *discordant* rate, not the headline pass rates. If your two conditions usually agree (small p_d), the same absolute effect needs many more tasks — measure p_d empirically on a pilot before committing to a task count."}],"resolvedModel":"claude-opus-4-8","totalDurationMs":129298,"totalTokens":28694,"totalToolUseCount":15,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":700,"cache_read_input_tokens":25205,"output_tokens":2787,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":700},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":2787,"cache_read_input_tokens":25205,"cache_creation_input_tokens":700,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":700,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":0,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":0,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":15}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"42a01d58-e1a5-4c55-9b1d-cff8e630e681","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"634480db-ad33-45ed-9650-e9877755f02c","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7ac81ca118e1dc58","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01YF8rvx1aZx9TfvxMSbwjjW","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive mechanism details and exact numbers across all five systems. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Verifier-Fed Skill Learning: The Trajectory→Skill→Future-Task Loop\n\nThe five systems converge on the same loop shape: **(1) run a task and get a verdict → (2) abstract the trajectory into a generalized, reusable note/skill → (3) store it keyed by similarity → (4) retrieve top-k and inject into context for a *new* related task.** The verifier (pass/fail or test-log feedback) gates *what gets written* and, in some systems, prunes what survives. Below, each system's concrete mechanism plus the headline numbers.\n\n## 1. Letta — \"Skill Learning\" (the source of the +9% → +15.7% figures)\n\n**Source:** https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning (vendor blog; primary source for these specific numbers, but self-reported, not peer-reviewed).\n\n**The loop (two stages):**\n- **Reflection stage:** given a finished trajectory, an LLM produces an assessment of task success, reasoning soundness, edge-case handling, and explicitly looks for \"repetitive patterns or actions that could be abstracted.\" This stage can be *enriched with textual feedback from task verifiers* (e.g., test logs identifying failure modes).\n- **Creation stage:** a learning agent (Letta Code) invokes Anthropic's **skill-creator** to write a skill containing \"potential approaches, common pitfalls, and verification strategies.\"\n\n**Storage/retrieval/injection:** skills are stored as **modular markdown `.md` files**, git-manageable and shareable across an org. They live in the Letta filesystem and are accessed by the agent during execution (the blog does not spell out an embedding-similarity retrieval step the way Voyager/ExpeL do — it leans on the filesystem/skills harness).\n\n**The exact numbers (on Terminal-Bench 2.0, 89 tasks):**\n- **Trajectory-only skills:** +21.1% relative / **+9% absolute** success, plus **15.7% lower cost** and **10.4% fewer tool calls**.\n- **Trajectory + verifier feedback skills:** an *additional* +6.7%, for **+36.8% relative / +15.7% absolute** over baseline.\n\n**What drove the jump from +9% to +15.7%:** adding **verifier/test-log textual feedback** into the reflection stage. Feedback-informed skills encode \"common failure modes and unsuccessful approaches,\" which trajectory-only skills miss (a successful trajectory shows what worked but not what to avoid). *Reliability note: this is the cleanest direct answer to the question, but it is a single vendor benchmark run on one suite.*\n\n**Related Letta framing:** https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning argues learning should happen in *token/context space* not weights (interpretable, portable across model generations, checkpointable), and proposes \"sleep-time compute\" to consolidate/de-duplicate/abstract memory between sessions. No benchmark numbers in that post — it's the conceptual backdrop for skill learning.\n\n## 2. Voyager — skill library gated by self-verification\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16291 / https://arxiv.org/html/2305.16291 (peer-reviewed-adjacent, NVIDIA/Caltech, widely cited — high reliability).\n\n- **Extraction:** skills are **executable code** (JS Mineflayer programs). A skill is written only after the task is solved.\n- **Verifier gates writing:** a *separate GPT-4 instance acts as a critic* — given the agent's state + task, it judges whether the program achieved the goal. Only on a pass is the skill committed. This is \"more comprehensive than self-reflection\" because it both checks success and reflects on mistakes for the retry loop.\n- **Storage/retrieval:** vector DB keyed by the **embedding of a GPT-3.5-generated natural-language description** of the program; value is the code. For a new task, retrieve **top-5** by embedding similarity of the self-generated plan + environment feedback.\n- **Injection:** retrieved skills + control-primitive APIs go into the prompt as in-context examples; complex skills are *composed* from simpler stored ones (compounding, anti-catastrophic-forgetting).\n- **Numbers:** **3.3× more unique items, 2.3× longer distance, tech-tree milestones up to 15.3× faster** (wood 15.3×, stone 8.5×, iron 6.4×). Key generalization result: in a *fresh* Minecraft world the learned library lets Voyager solve novel tasks that baselines \"cannot solve any\" of.\n\n## 3. ExpeL — insight pool with vote-based pruning\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144 / https://arxiv.org/html/2308.10144v3 (AAAI 2024 — high reliability).\n\n- **Extraction (two channels):** (a) **compare success/fail trajectory pairs of the same task** to surface what distinguished the win; (b) extract common \"good practices\" from groups of L successes across different tasks.\n- **Verifier-driven refinement = the most explicit pruning mechanism here.** Insights live in a pool maintained by four LLM operations: **ADD** (new insight, importance count starts at 2), **EDIT** and **UPVOTE** (increment count), **DOWNVOTE** (decrement). **An insight is deleted when its importance hits zero.** This is the concrete \"prune skills\" answer.\n- **Retrieval/injection:** at inference, retrieve **top-k successful trajectories** by max inner-product task similarity (all-mpnet-base-v2 embeddings, Faiss), and inject **the full insight list + those top-k trajectories** as in-context guidance.\n- **Numbers (vs ReAct):** HotpotQA 39% vs 28%; ALFWorld 59% vs 40%; WebShop 49% vs 11%; **transfer** to FEVER 70% vs 63% (demonstrates source-task knowledge helping a *different* target task).\n\n## 4. Agent Workflow Memory (AWM) — induced reusable routines\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.07429 / https://arxiv.org/html/2409.07429v1 (CMU; Wang/Mao/Fried/Neubig — high reliability).\n\n- **Extraction by induction:** an LM extracts common **sub-routines (workflows)** from past successful trajectories, *abstracting* concrete details into variables (e.g., \"dry cat food\" → \"{product-name}\") for generalization. Each workflow = NL goal description + step sequence (state → reasoning → action).\n- **Verifier:** in **online** mode, after each test query the agent solves it, an **LM-based evaluator emits a binary success label**, and *only successful* trajectories are induced into workflows and added to memory (M + {w} → M'). This is the on-the-fly, no-training-set variant.\n- **Injection:** workflows become auxiliary memory folded into the system prompt for subsequent tasks.\n- **Numbers:** **+24.6% relative** success on Mind2Web, **+51.1% relative** on WebArena (plus fewer steps). Online AWM generalizes cross-task/site/domain by **+8.9 to +14.0 absolute points**, with the margin *widening* as the train/test gap grows — strong evidence the skills help on genuinely new tasks, not the same ones.\n\n## 5. Reflexion — verbal RL (the precursor; mostly same-task but the mechanism root)\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366 (NeurIPS 2023 — high reliability).\n\n- **Loop:** convert binary/scalar environment feedback into a **verbal self-reflection**, store it in an **episodic memory buffer**, and prepend it as context on the **next trial** of the task. The reflection acts as a \"semantic gradient.\"\n- **Verifier role:** the pass/fail signal is what's turned into the reflection — refinement *guided by* the verdict beats refinement alone by an **+8% absolute** boost over plain episodic memory.\n- *Caveat for this angle:* Reflexion primarily improves *retries of the same task* across trials, not transfer to new tasks. It's the conceptual root that ExpeL/AWM/Letta extend toward cross-task reuse.\n\n---\n\n## Synthesis — the common verifier-fed loop\n1. **Solve + judge:** run the trajectory; a verifier (env reward, separate-LLM critic, or test logs) yields pass/fail + optional textual diagnosis.\n2. **Abstract, don't memorize:** an LLM induces a *generalized* artifact — code skill (Voyager), NL insight (ExpeL), workflow with variables (AWM), markdown skill with pitfalls + verification strategy (Letta). Variabilizing/abstracting is what makes it help *future* tasks.\n3. **Gate on the verdict:** only verified-good experiences are written (Voyager, AWM); failures feed the *content* of the note (\"what to avoid\") rather than being discarded — this is exactly Letta's +9%→+15.7% lever.\n4. **Store by similarity, retrieve top-k, inject:** embedding-keyed vector store with top-5/top-k retrieval (Voyager, ExpeL) or filesystem/memory blocks (Letta, AWM); inject as in-context examples/auxiliary memory.\n5. **Prune:** ExpeL's UPVOTE/DOWNVOTE-to-zero is the most concrete pruning; Letta proposes sleep-time consolidation; others mainly accrete.\n\n**Most relevant for the Yogi build:** ExpeL's vote-based insight pruning and AWM's verifier-gated online induction are the most directly implementable \"verifier refines/prunes skills\" mechanisms; Letta's blog is the source of the specific +9%/+15.7% Terminal-Bench-2.0 numbers and confirms that **verifier feedback in the reflection step is the differentiating ingredient.**\n\n**Reliability summary:** Voyager, ExpeL, AWM, Reflexion are peer-reviewed/established papers (high confidence). The Letta +9%/+15.7% figures are vendor-self-reported on a single benchmark run (directionally credible, treat the exact magnitudes with appropriate caution)."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a1a2b12365cad33d6 (use SendMessage with to: 'a1a2b12365cad33d6' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 28674\ntool_uses: 12\nduration_ms: 124832</usage>"}]}]},"uuid":"5f380707-bb42-4744-8665-151d9e26c8d1","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:15:58.081Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Verifier-fed skill learning, concretely. From Letta's skill-learning work (and similar systems like Voyager, ExpeL, Agent Workflow Memory, Reflexion, \"agentic memory\"): what is the LOOP that turns a solved or failed trajectory into a reusable SKILL NOTE that helps on FUTURE related tasks (not the same task)? Specifically:\n- How is a skill extracted from a trajectory (summarization, induction)?\n- How are skills stored, retrieved, and injected into context for new tasks?\n- How does a verifier (pass/fail signal, self-critique) refine or prune skills?\n- What specifically drove Letta's reported jump from +9% to +15.7% (or similar numbers)? Find the actual Letta blog/paper on skill learning.\n\nSearch queries to try: \"Letta skill learning agent blog\", \"Letta filesystem skills self-improving agent\", \"Voyager skill library Minecraft LLM\", \"ExpeL experiential learning agent\", \"Agent Workflow Memory induction\", \"Reflexion verbal reinforcement learning\", \"agent learns reusable skills from trajectories verifier\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch 6-8 relevant pages (Letta blog, arxiv papers for Voyager/ExpeL/AWM/Reflexion). Extract concrete mechanism details and the specific performance numbers with their source. Return findings only as your final message, each with claim + source URL + reliability note.","agentId":"a1a2b12365cad33d6","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive mechanism details and exact numbers across all five systems. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Verifier-Fed Skill Learning: The Trajectory→Skill→Future-Task Loop\n\nThe five systems converge on the same loop shape: **(1) run a task and get a verdict → (2) abstract the trajectory into a generalized, reusable note/skill → (3) store it keyed by similarity → (4) retrieve top-k and inject into context for a *new* related task.** The verifier (pass/fail or test-log feedback) gates *what gets written* and, in some systems, prunes what survives. Below, each system's concrete mechanism plus the headline numbers.\n\n## 1. Letta — \"Skill Learning\" (the source of the +9% → +15.7% figures)\n\n**Source:** https://www.letta.com/blog/skill-learning (vendor blog; primary source for these specific numbers, but self-reported, not peer-reviewed).\n\n**The loop (two stages):**\n- **Reflection stage:** given a finished trajectory, an LLM produces an assessment of task success, reasoning soundness, edge-case handling, and explicitly looks for \"repetitive patterns or actions that could be abstracted.\" This stage can be *enriched with textual feedback from task verifiers* (e.g., test logs identifying failure modes).\n- **Creation stage:** a learning agent (Letta Code) invokes Anthropic's **skill-creator** to write a skill containing \"potential approaches, common pitfalls, and verification strategies.\"\n\n**Storage/retrieval/injection:** skills are stored as **modular markdown `.md` files**, git-manageable and shareable across an org. They live in the Letta filesystem and are accessed by the agent during execution (the blog does not spell out an embedding-similarity retrieval step the way Voyager/ExpeL do — it leans on the filesystem/skills harness).\n\n**The exact numbers (on Terminal-Bench 2.0, 89 tasks):**\n- **Trajectory-only skills:** +21.1% relative / **+9% absolute** success, plus **15.7% lower cost** and **10.4% fewer tool calls**.\n- **Trajectory + verifier feedback skills:** an *additional* +6.7%, for **+36.8% relative / +15.7% absolute** over baseline.\n\n**What drove the jump from +9% to +15.7%:** adding **verifier/test-log textual feedback** into the reflection stage. Feedback-informed skills encode \"common failure modes and unsuccessful approaches,\" which trajectory-only skills miss (a successful trajectory shows what worked but not what to avoid). *Reliability note: this is the cleanest direct answer to the question, but it is a single vendor benchmark run on one suite.*\n\n**Related Letta framing:** https://www.letta.com/blog/continual-learning argues learning should happen in *token/context space* not weights (interpretable, portable across model generations, checkpointable), and proposes \"sleep-time compute\" to consolidate/de-duplicate/abstract memory between sessions. No benchmark numbers in that post — it's the conceptual backdrop for skill learning.\n\n## 2. Voyager — skill library gated by self-verification\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16291 / https://arxiv.org/html/2305.16291 (peer-reviewed-adjacent, NVIDIA/Caltech, widely cited — high reliability).\n\n- **Extraction:** skills are **executable code** (JS Mineflayer programs). A skill is written only after the task is solved.\n- **Verifier gates writing:** a *separate GPT-4 instance acts as a critic* — given the agent's state + task, it judges whether the program achieved the goal. Only on a pass is the skill committed. This is \"more comprehensive than self-reflection\" because it both checks success and reflects on mistakes for the retry loop.\n- **Storage/retrieval:** vector DB keyed by the **embedding of a GPT-3.5-generated natural-language description** of the program; value is the code. For a new task, retrieve **top-5** by embedding similarity of the self-generated plan + environment feedback.\n- **Injection:** retrieved skills + control-primitive APIs go into the prompt as in-context examples; complex skills are *composed* from simpler stored ones (compounding, anti-catastrophic-forgetting).\n- **Numbers:** **3.3× more unique items, 2.3× longer distance, tech-tree milestones up to 15.3× faster** (wood 15.3×, stone 8.5×, iron 6.4×). Key generalization result: in a *fresh* Minecraft world the learned library lets Voyager solve novel tasks that baselines \"cannot solve any\" of.\n\n## 3. ExpeL — insight pool with vote-based pruning\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2308.10144 / https://arxiv.org/html/2308.10144v3 (AAAI 2024 — high reliability).\n\n- **Extraction (two channels):** (a) **compare success/fail trajectory pairs of the same task** to surface what distinguished the win; (b) extract common \"good practices\" from groups of L successes across different tasks.\n- **Verifier-driven refinement = the most explicit pruning mechanism here.** Insights live in a pool maintained by four LLM operations: **ADD** (new insight, importance count starts at 2), **EDIT** and **UPVOTE** (increment count), **DOWNVOTE** (decrement). **An insight is deleted when its importance hits zero.** This is the concrete \"prune skills\" answer.\n- **Retrieval/injection:** at inference, retrieve **top-k successful trajectories** by max inner-product task similarity (all-mpnet-base-v2 embeddings, Faiss), and inject **the full insight list + those top-k trajectories** as in-context guidance.\n- **Numbers (vs ReAct):** HotpotQA 39% vs 28%; ALFWorld 59% vs 40%; WebShop 49% vs 11%; **transfer** to FEVER 70% vs 63% (demonstrates source-task knowledge helping a *different* target task).\n\n## 4. Agent Workflow Memory (AWM) — induced reusable routines\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2409.07429 / https://arxiv.org/html/2409.07429v1 (CMU; Wang/Mao/Fried/Neubig — high reliability).\n\n- **Extraction by induction:** an LM extracts common **sub-routines (workflows)** from past successful trajectories, *abstracting* concrete details into variables (e.g., \"dry cat food\" → \"{product-name}\") for generalization. Each workflow = NL goal description + step sequence (state → reasoning → action).\n- **Verifier:** in **online** mode, after each test query the agent solves it, an **LM-based evaluator emits a binary success label**, and *only successful* trajectories are induced into workflows and added to memory (M + {w} → M'). This is the on-the-fly, no-training-set variant.\n- **Injection:** workflows become auxiliary memory folded into the system prompt for subsequent tasks.\n- **Numbers:** **+24.6% relative** success on Mind2Web, **+51.1% relative** on WebArena (plus fewer steps). Online AWM generalizes cross-task/site/domain by **+8.9 to +14.0 absolute points**, with the margin *widening* as the train/test gap grows — strong evidence the skills help on genuinely new tasks, not the same ones.\n\n## 5. Reflexion — verbal RL (the precursor; mostly same-task but the mechanism root)\n\n**Source:** https://arxiv.org/abs/2303.11366 (NeurIPS 2023 — high reliability).\n\n- **Loop:** convert binary/scalar environment feedback into a **verbal self-reflection**, store it in an **episodic memory buffer**, and prepend it as context on the **next trial** of the task. The reflection acts as a \"semantic gradient.\"\n- **Verifier role:** the pass/fail signal is what's turned into the reflection — refinement *guided by* the verdict beats refinement alone by an **+8% absolute** boost over plain episodic memory.\n- *Caveat for this angle:* Reflexion primarily improves *retries of the same task* across trials, not transfer to new tasks. It's the conceptual root that ExpeL/AWM/Letta extend toward cross-task reuse.\n\n---\n\n## Synthesis — the common verifier-fed loop\n1. **Solve + judge:** run the trajectory; a verifier (env reward, separate-LLM critic, or test logs) yields pass/fail + optional textual diagnosis.\n2. **Abstract, don't memorize:** an LLM induces a *generalized* artifact — code skill (Voyager), NL insight (ExpeL), workflow with variables (AWM), markdown skill with pitfalls + verification strategy (Letta). Variabilizing/abstracting is what makes it help *future* tasks.\n3. **Gate on the verdict:** only verified-good experiences are written (Voyager, AWM); failures feed the *content* of the note (\"what to avoid\") rather than being discarded — this is exactly Letta's +9%→+15.7% lever.\n4. **Store by similarity, retrieve top-k, inject:** embedding-keyed vector store with top-5/top-k retrieval (Voyager, ExpeL) or filesystem/memory blocks (Letta, AWM); inject as in-context examples/auxiliary memory.\n5. **Prune:** ExpeL's UPVOTE/DOWNVOTE-to-zero is the most concrete pruning; Letta proposes sleep-time consolidation; others mainly accrete.\n\n**Most relevant for the Yogi build:** ExpeL's vote-based insight pruning and AWM's verifier-gated online induction are the most directly implementable \"verifier refines/prunes skills\" mechanisms; Letta's blog is the source of the specific +9%/+15.7% Terminal-Bench-2.0 numbers and confirms that **verifier feedback in the reflection step is the differentiating ingredient.**\n\n**Reliability summary:** Voyager, ExpeL, AWM, Reflexion are peer-reviewed/established papers (high confidence). The Letta +9%/+15.7% figures are vendor-self-reported on a single benchmark run (directionally credible, treat the exact magnitudes with appropriate caution)."}],"resolvedModel":"claude-opus-4-8","totalDurationMs":124832,"totalTokens":28674,"totalToolUseCount":12,"usage":{"input_tokens":2,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2461,"cache_read_input_tokens":22706,"output_tokens":3505,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2461},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":2,"output_tokens":3505,"cache_read_input_tokens":22706,"cache_creation_input_tokens":2461,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":2461,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":0,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":0,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":12}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"634480db-ad33-45ed-9650-e9877755f02c","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"86e95bd6-0df9-4078-b8dd-1f12b948462a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7ac81ca118e1dc58","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_014weBmMb6LZRLes1LkGhHFw","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive coverage. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Findings: Memorization vs. Generalization in Memory/Agent Benchmarks\n\n## A. Anti-recall corpus-design rules that actually work (LongMemEval family)\n\n**1. Parametric-knowledge filtering (\"can the model already answer it cold?\").** LongMemEval-V2 filters every question so it is NOT answerable from the model's weights alone: a question is kept only if \"at least two out of four models answered the questions incorrectly\" when tested *without trajectory context* (against Gemini-3-Pro, GPT-5.2, Grok-4.1, Claude-Opus-4.6). This is the single most concrete anti-leakage rule found — it directly screens out questions a model can answer by lookup/priors.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1\n- Reliability: High — arXiv paper, explicit rule.\n\n**2. Oracle/no-context pilot study to detect leakage.** LongMemEval v1 ran a pilot checking (a) whether questions are answerable *without* trajectory evidence, and (b) whether oracle access to answer-bearing sessions suffices. The reported gap is load-bearing: GPT-4o scores ~92% in the oracle (only answer-containing sessions given) condition but ~58% in the full interactive setting — a ~34-point drop attributed to retrieval/integration, not recall.\n- Sources: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 , https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/longmemeval\n- Reliability: High (paper) / Medium (summary site corroborates numbers).\n\n**3. Indirect information embedding.** Facts are never stated as the answer; they must be inferred. Example: instead of \"I bought a new car,\" the user asks for car-insurance help, *incidentally* revealing the purchase. Forces comprehension over surface matching.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 — Reliability: High.\n\n**4. Evidence distributed across sessions + diverse intra-session placement.** Most questions need evidence from *multiple* sessions (up to six); annotators deliberately scatter evidence across positions so no single session/lookup answers it. This is the operational definition of \"multi-hop\" in the benchmark.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 — Reliability: High.\n\n**5. Temporal grounding with mixed explicit/colloquial time cues.** Timestamps (metadata) plus natural-language references (\"last weekend,\" \"three months ago\") that must be aligned — naive similarity retrieval cannot solve these.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 — Reliability: High.\n\n**6. Knowledge-update task = held-out-by-time-of-fact.** A fact is changed across sessions (job, preference); the system must return the *current* value, not the stale stored one. This tests whether a stored \"answer\" is correctly superseded — a form of transfer over recall.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 — Reliability: High.\n\n**7. Abstention / false-premise split.** ~30 questions are converted into false-premise variants (asking about something never mentioned); correct behavior is to refuse, not to retrieve. Tests that a system isn't pattern-matching a plausible answer. LongMemEval-V2 calls this \"premise awareness\" and treats it as a distinct transfer dimension.\n- Sources: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 , https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1 — Reliability: High.\n\n**8. Goal/hint sanitization (V2).** V2 removed explicit navigation hints from WorkArena/WorkArena++ goals \"to prevent procedure questions answerable by reading the route directly.\" Concrete rule: strip any text where the question text itself leaks the procedure/answer.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1 — Reliability: High.\n\n**9. Realistic distractor haystack.** Irrelevant sessions sampled from self-chat (non-conflicting attributes) + public ShareGPT/UltraChat, inserted with plausible timestamps; context up to ~115k tokens (S) / ~1.5M (M, 500 sessions); V2 pushes to 25M–115M tokens. Forces relevant/irrelevant discrimination rather than dumping everything.\n- Sources: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 , https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1 — Reliability: High.\n\n## B. LoCoMo — the cautionary tale (what NOT to do)\n\n**10. Corrupted gold answers cap the ceiling.** An audit documents ~99 wrong/hallucinated/misattributed/ambiguous ground-truth answers across the 10 conversations, implying an honest ceiling of ~93–94% (so 100% claims are mathematically implausible). Concrete example: gold answer for \"What might John's degree be in?\" is \"Political science / Public administration,\" yet in the cited session John shares a *Graphic Design* certificate.\n- Sources: https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29 — Reliability: Medium-High (detailed third-party audit, but adversarial context — it's a benchmarking dispute thread).\n\n**11. top_k bypasses retrieval entirely.** Session counts per conversation are 19/19/32/29/29/28/31/30/25/30. Setting `top_k=50` exceeds every count, so the system retrieves the whole conversation — the embedding step becomes a no-op and the task degenerates to \"dump everything into the LLM.\" Honest numbers: 60.3% recall@10 (no rerank), 88.9% recall@10 (hybrid, no LLM).\n- Source: https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29 — Reliability: Medium-High (same audit).\n\n**12. Category-5 inflation / task-type confusion.** LoCoMo ships 1,986 QA pairs but 446 are category-5 (adversarial/unanswerable, documented ground-truth problems). The published convention is to evaluate the 1,540 non-adversarial subset, because cat-5 tests *refusal*, not recall — reporting \"1,986 multi-hop questions\" conflates two different tasks and inflates size. Mem0 explicitly excluded the adversarial category (\"ground truth answers were unavailable\").\n- Sources: https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29 , https://arxiv.org/html/2504.19413v1 — Reliability: High (Mem0 quote is from the paper).\n\n**13. Single-hop vs multi-hop category misalignment.** The numerical-ID → semantic-category mapping in LoCoMo is ambiguous and has caused mislabeled multi-hop/single-hop reporting across several papers — i.e., people report \"multi-hop\" scores that include single-hop lookups.\n- Source web summary of https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/locomo-benchmark-scores — Reliability: Medium (secondary summary).\n\n**14. Filesystem baseline ≈ sophisticated memory systems.** A Letta agent with plain filesystem tools hit 74.0% on LoCoMo (GPT-4o-mini), beating Mem0's reported top graph variant at 68.5%. Letta's framing: LoCoMo measures \"retrieval from long conversations,\" not agentic memory, and simple tools win partly because they're in-distribution for the LLM. Implication: if a trivial baseline matches your system, the benchmark isn't isolating the capability.\n- Source: https://www.letta.com/blog/benchmarking-ai-agent-memory/ — Reliability: Medium-High (vendor blog, but specific reproducible numbers; vendor has incentive).\n\n## C. The recall-vs-reasoning metric-conflation critique (cross-cutting)\n\n**15. Retrieval-recall ≠ end-to-end QA — gaps of 20–30 points.** A recurring critique: systems report retrieval metrics (recall@k) and compare them against QA-accuracy leaderboards. Concrete instance: a system reported 96.6% `recall_any@5` but independent end-to-end QA (retrieve → answer → judge) was 82.6%; another reported 95.2% R@5 *explicitly labeled non-QA*. Rule proposed: always report retrieval and synthesis separately, because the 20–30pt gap *is* the reasoning/transfer signal.\n- Sources: https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/discussions/747 , https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29 — Reliability: Medium-High (benchmarking-dispute threads, but quote specific runs).\n\n**16. Post-hoc held-out splits violate pre-registration.** The 100% LoCoMo path used three hand-coded patches targeting specific failing questions, with the \"held-out\" split created *after* the patches — i.e., the test set was designed around known answers. Rule: held-out/transfer splits must be fixed before any system tuning.\n- Source: https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29 — Reliability: Medium-High.\n\n**17. Mem0's own protocol (for reference).** Mem0 evaluates 4 LoCoMo categories (single-hop, multi-hop, temporal, open-domain), excludes adversarial, uses LLM-as-judge (primary) + F1/BLEU-1 (acknowledged weak), end-to-end QA, 10 runs ±1 SD, ~26k-token / ~600-turn conversations. This is end-to-end, not retrieval-only — a positive contrast to #15.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2504.19413v1 — Reliability: High.\n\n## D. General agent-benchmark principles (transfer vs memorization)\n\n**18. Many agent benchmarks have no holdout — so agents overfit.** \"AI Agents That Matter\" (Kapoor et al.) states agent benchmarks \"have inadequate holdout sets, and sometimes none at all,\" producing agents \"fragile because they take shortcuts and overfit to the benchmark\"; they prescribe \"a principled framework for avoiding overfitting.\" Overfitting is acute because benchmarks are small (a few hundred samples).\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.01502 (abstract; full PDF didn't render) — Reliability: High (peer-reviewed, ICLR).\n\n**19. Domain-general benchmarks need held-out *tasks*, not just held-out *answers*.** If a benchmark claims domain-generality but lacks held-out tasks, developers shortcut to the specific tasks present, yielding agents that don't transfer within the domain. ALFWorld is cited as a positive model: its Transfer Learning phase tests new *instances within known categories*, forcing procedural learning over trajectory memorization. This is the cleanest articulation of the transfer rule: split by *task/category*, not by *answer*.\n- Source: web summary of https://arxiv.org/pdf/2407.01502 — Reliability: Medium (secondary summary of the paper).\n\n**20. Memorization-detection methods exist.** Compare passing agent solutions to gold patches via Jaccard / difflib sequence-matcher ratio to flag regurgitated vs. independently generated answers — a usable contamination check.\n- Source: web summary (SWE-bench-adjacent work) — Reliability: Medium.\n\n**21. Contamination is broader than verbatim leakage.** Paraphrased/semantically-near questions, solution fragments, distilled or synthetic samples all leak; \"synthetic data generation introduces detectable patterns models exploit rather than demonstrating genuine memory\" (a LoCoMo-specific charge). Rule: dedupe at the semantic level, not just string level.\n- Sources: https://thegrigorian.medium.com/when-benchmarks-lie-... , LoCoMo-criticism summary — Reliability: Medium (blog + secondary).\n\n**22. ConvoMem: \"your first 150 conversations don't need RAG.\"** Argues LoCoMo/LongMemEval are too small to stress memory and \"suffer from answer leakage, where answers inadvertently appear in context.\" Its design rules: explicit separation of recall tasks vs reasoning/transfer tasks; held-out test sets; systematic validation against answer leakage; questions testing both direct retrieval and inference across history.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.10523 — Reliability: Medium-High (arXiv preprint; the leakage claim about prior benchmarks is the paper's framing/motivation).\n\n---\n\n## Distilled corpus-design rules for a memory benchmark that tests TRANSFER, not lookup\n1. **Filter by cold-answerability** — drop any question the base model answers without the stored memory (LongMemEval-V2's \"2-of-4 models wrong\" rule). [#1]\n2. **Split by task/category, not by answer** — held-out *variants* of known task types (ALFWorld pattern); fix the split before any tuning. [#16, #19]\n3. **Force multi-hop** — require evidence from ≥2 sessions, scattered in position; label the required evidence hops. [#4]\n4. **Embed facts indirectly** — never state the answer; require inference. [#3]\n5. **Include knowledge-update items** — a stored answer must be superseded by a later fact (recall would *fail* this). [#6]\n6. **Include false-premise/abstention items** — correct behavior is refusal; tests against confident pattern-matching. [#7]\n7. **Mix explicit + colloquial temporal cues** to defeat similarity retrieval. [#5]\n8. **Report retrieval and end-to-end QA separately** — the gap is the reasoning signal; never compare recall@k to QA accuracy. [#15]\n9. **Sanity-check with a trivial baseline** (filesystem/dump-all) — if it matches your system, the benchmark isn't isolating memory. [#14]\n10. **Validate gold answers and avoid top_k ≥ corpus size**, which bypasses retrieval entirely. [#10, #11]\n11. **Semantic (not just string) dedup** against the training corpus to catch paraphrase leakage. [#21]\n\nNote: the strongest *positive* design rules come from the LongMemEval papers (arXiv, high reliability). The strongest *critiques* of LoCoMo come from a benchmarking-dispute GitHub thread (MemPalace issue #29 / discussion #747) and Letta's vendor blog — concrete and number-backed, but adversarial in origin, so treat the specific accusations as Medium-High rather than definitive."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: a426968626a78bc3d (use SendMessage with to: 'a426968626a78bc3d' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 35495\ntool_uses: 17\nduration_ms: 157429</usage>"}]}]},"uuid":"7abe77e5-3fb4-4eca-bbd0-b13c28e14f2d","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:16:15.660Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Memorization vs. generalization in memory/agent benchmarks. How do LoCoMo, LongMemEval, Letta memory benchmarks, and Mem0 avoid measuring trivial answer-lookup / recall? What corpus-design rules make a memory benchmark test TRANSFER (a stored lesson helps on NEW but related tasks) rather than recall of a stored answer? Look for: train/test separation by task vs by answer, held-out variants, paraphrase/transfer splits, multi-hop vs single-hop questions, \"answer leakage\" critiques of these benchmarks.\n\nSearch queries to try: \"LongMemEval benchmark abstention reasoning\", \"LoCoMo benchmark criticism multi-hop\", \"Mem0 benchmark methodology answer lookup\", \"Letta memory benchmark generalization\", \"memory benchmark answer leakage contamination\", \"agent benchmark transfer vs memorization held-out\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch the 6-8 most relevant pages (arxiv papers, blog posts from Letta/Mem0, benchmark repos). Extract concrete, falsifiable claims. Return a list of findings each with: the claim, the source URL, and a one-line note on reliability. Be concrete about corpus-design rules. Return findings only as your final message.","agentId":"a426968626a78bc3d","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive coverage. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n# Findings: Memorization vs. Generalization in Memory/Agent Benchmarks\n\n## A. Anti-recall corpus-design rules that actually work (LongMemEval family)\n\n**1. Parametric-knowledge filtering (\"can the model already answer it cold?\").** LongMemEval-V2 filters every question so it is NOT answerable from the model's weights alone: a question is kept only if \"at least two out of four models answered the questions incorrectly\" when tested *without trajectory context* (against Gemini-3-Pro, GPT-5.2, Grok-4.1, Claude-Opus-4.6). This is the single most concrete anti-leakage rule found — it directly screens out questions a model can answer by lookup/priors.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1\n- Reliability: High — arXiv paper, explicit rule.\n\n**2. Oracle/no-context pilot study to detect leakage.** LongMemEval v1 ran a pilot checking (a) whether questions are answerable *without* trajectory evidence, and (b) whether oracle access to answer-bearing sessions suffices. The reported gap is load-bearing: GPT-4o scores ~92% in the oracle (only answer-containing sessions given) condition but ~58% in the full interactive setting — a ~34-point drop attributed to retrieval/integration, not recall.\n- Sources: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 , https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/longmemeval\n- Reliability: High (paper) / Medium (summary site corroborates numbers).\n\n**3. Indirect information embedding.** Facts are never stated as the answer; they must be inferred. Example: instead of \"I bought a new car,\" the user asks for car-insurance help, *incidentally* revealing the purchase. Forces comprehension over surface matching.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 — Reliability: High.\n\n**4. Evidence distributed across sessions + diverse intra-session placement.** Most questions need evidence from *multiple* sessions (up to six); annotators deliberately scatter evidence across positions so no single session/lookup answers it. This is the operational definition of \"multi-hop\" in the benchmark.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 — Reliability: High.\n\n**5. Temporal grounding with mixed explicit/colloquial time cues.** Timestamps (metadata) plus natural-language references (\"last weekend,\" \"three months ago\") that must be aligned — naive similarity retrieval cannot solve these.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 — Reliability: High.\n\n**6. Knowledge-update task = held-out-by-time-of-fact.** A fact is changed across sessions (job, preference); the system must return the *current* value, not the stale stored one. This tests whether a stored \"answer\" is correctly superseded — a form of transfer over recall.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 — Reliability: High.\n\n**7. Abstention / false-premise split.** ~30 questions are converted into false-premise variants (asking about something never mentioned); correct behavior is to refuse, not to retrieve. Tests that a system isn't pattern-matching a plausible answer. LongMemEval-V2 calls this \"premise awareness\" and treats it as a distinct transfer dimension.\n- Sources: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 , https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1 — Reliability: High.\n\n**8. Goal/hint sanitization (V2).** V2 removed explicit navigation hints from WorkArena/WorkArena++ goals \"to prevent procedure questions answerable by reading the route directly.\" Concrete rule: strip any text where the question text itself leaks the procedure/answer.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1 — Reliability: High.\n\n**9. Realistic distractor haystack.** Irrelevant sessions sampled from self-chat (non-conflicting attributes) + public ShareGPT/UltraChat, inserted with plausible timestamps; context up to ~115k tokens (S) / ~1.5M (M, 500 sessions); V2 pushes to 25M–115M tokens. Forces relevant/irrelevant discrimination rather than dumping everything.\n- Sources: https://arxiv.org/html/2410.10813v2 , https://arxiv.org/html/2605.12493v1 — Reliability: High.\n\n## B. LoCoMo — the cautionary tale (what NOT to do)\n\n**10. Corrupted gold answers cap the ceiling.** An audit documents ~99 wrong/hallucinated/misattributed/ambiguous ground-truth answers across the 10 conversations, implying an honest ceiling of ~93–94% (so 100% claims are mathematically implausible). Concrete example: gold answer for \"What might John's degree be in?\" is \"Political science / Public administration,\" yet in the cited session John shares a *Graphic Design* certificate.\n- Sources: https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29 — Reliability: Medium-High (detailed third-party audit, but adversarial context — it's a benchmarking dispute thread).\n\n**11. top_k bypasses retrieval entirely.** Session counts per conversation are 19/19/32/29/29/28/31/30/25/30. Setting `top_k=50` exceeds every count, so the system retrieves the whole conversation — the embedding step becomes a no-op and the task degenerates to \"dump everything into the LLM.\" Honest numbers: 60.3% recall@10 (no rerank), 88.9% recall@10 (hybrid, no LLM).\n- Source: https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29 — Reliability: Medium-High (same audit).\n\n**12. Category-5 inflation / task-type confusion.** LoCoMo ships 1,986 QA pairs but 446 are category-5 (adversarial/unanswerable, documented ground-truth problems). The published convention is to evaluate the 1,540 non-adversarial subset, because cat-5 tests *refusal*, not recall — reporting \"1,986 multi-hop questions\" conflates two different tasks and inflates size. Mem0 explicitly excluded the adversarial category (\"ground truth answers were unavailable\").\n- Sources: https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29 , https://arxiv.org/html/2504.19413v1 — Reliability: High (Mem0 quote is from the paper).\n\n**13. Single-hop vs multi-hop category misalignment.** The numerical-ID → semantic-category mapping in LoCoMo is ambiguous and has caused mislabeled multi-hop/single-hop reporting across several papers — i.e., people report \"multi-hop\" scores that include single-hop lookups.\n- Source web summary of https://www.emergentmind.com/topics/locomo-benchmark-scores — Reliability: Medium (secondary summary).\n\n**14. Filesystem baseline ≈ sophisticated memory systems.** A Letta agent with plain filesystem tools hit 74.0% on LoCoMo (GPT-4o-mini), beating Mem0's reported top graph variant at 68.5%. Letta's framing: LoCoMo measures \"retrieval from long conversations,\" not agentic memory, and simple tools win partly because they're in-distribution for the LLM. Implication: if a trivial baseline matches your system, the benchmark isn't isolating the capability.\n- Source: https://www.letta.com/blog/benchmarking-ai-agent-memory/ — Reliability: Medium-High (vendor blog, but specific reproducible numbers; vendor has incentive).\n\n## C. The recall-vs-reasoning metric-conflation critique (cross-cutting)\n\n**15. Retrieval-recall ≠ end-to-end QA — gaps of 20–30 points.** A recurring critique: systems report retrieval metrics (recall@k) and compare them against QA-accuracy leaderboards. Concrete instance: a system reported 96.6% `recall_any@5` but independent end-to-end QA (retrieve → answer → judge) was 82.6%; another reported 95.2% R@5 *explicitly labeled non-QA*. Rule proposed: always report retrieval and synthesis separately, because the 20–30pt gap *is* the reasoning/transfer signal.\n- Sources: https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/discussions/747 , https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29 — Reliability: Medium-High (benchmarking-dispute threads, but quote specific runs).\n\n**16. Post-hoc held-out splits violate pre-registration.** The 100% LoCoMo path used three hand-coded patches targeting specific failing questions, with the \"held-out\" split created *after* the patches — i.e., the test set was designed around known answers. Rule: held-out/transfer splits must be fixed before any system tuning.\n- Source: https://github.com/MemPalace/mempalace/issues/29 — Reliability: Medium-High.\n\n**17. Mem0's own protocol (for reference).** Mem0 evaluates 4 LoCoMo categories (single-hop, multi-hop, temporal, open-domain), excludes adversarial, uses LLM-as-judge (primary) + F1/BLEU-1 (acknowledged weak), end-to-end QA, 10 runs ±1 SD, ~26k-token / ~600-turn conversations. This is end-to-end, not retrieval-only — a positive contrast to #15.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2504.19413v1 — Reliability: High.\n\n## D. General agent-benchmark principles (transfer vs memorization)\n\n**18. Many agent benchmarks have no holdout — so agents overfit.** \"AI Agents That Matter\" (Kapoor et al.) states agent benchmarks \"have inadequate holdout sets, and sometimes none at all,\" producing agents \"fragile because they take shortcuts and overfit to the benchmark\"; they prescribe \"a principled framework for avoiding overfitting.\" Overfitting is acute because benchmarks are small (a few hundred samples).\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2407.01502 (abstract; full PDF didn't render) — Reliability: High (peer-reviewed, ICLR).\n\n**19. Domain-general benchmarks need held-out *tasks*, not just held-out *answers*.** If a benchmark claims domain-generality but lacks held-out tasks, developers shortcut to the specific tasks present, yielding agents that don't transfer within the domain. ALFWorld is cited as a positive model: its Transfer Learning phase tests new *instances within known categories*, forcing procedural learning over trajectory memorization. This is the cleanest articulation of the transfer rule: split by *task/category*, not by *answer*.\n- Source: web summary of https://arxiv.org/pdf/2407.01502 — Reliability: Medium (secondary summary of the paper).\n\n**20. Memorization-detection methods exist.** Compare passing agent solutions to gold patches via Jaccard / difflib sequence-matcher ratio to flag regurgitated vs. independently generated answers — a usable contamination check.\n- Source: web summary (SWE-bench-adjacent work) — Reliability: Medium.\n\n**21. Contamination is broader than verbatim leakage.** Paraphrased/semantically-near questions, solution fragments, distilled or synthetic samples all leak; \"synthetic data generation introduces detectable patterns models exploit rather than demonstrating genuine memory\" (a LoCoMo-specific charge). Rule: dedupe at the semantic level, not just string level.\n- Sources: https://thegrigorian.medium.com/when-benchmarks-lie-... , LoCoMo-criticism summary — Reliability: Medium (blog + secondary).\n\n**22. ConvoMem: \"your first 150 conversations don't need RAG.\"** Argues LoCoMo/LongMemEval are too small to stress memory and \"suffer from answer leakage, where answers inadvertently appear in context.\" Its design rules: explicit separation of recall tasks vs reasoning/transfer tasks; held-out test sets; systematic validation against answer leakage; questions testing both direct retrieval and inference across history.\n- Source: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2511.10523 — Reliability: Medium-High (arXiv preprint; the leakage claim about prior benchmarks is the paper's framing/motivation).\n\n---\n\n## Distilled corpus-design rules for a memory benchmark that tests TRANSFER, not lookup\n1. **Filter by cold-answerability** — drop any question the base model answers without the stored memory (LongMemEval-V2's \"2-of-4 models wrong\" rule). [#1]\n2. **Split by task/category, not by answer** — held-out *variants* of known task types (ALFWorld pattern); fix the split before any tuning. [#16, #19]\n3. **Force multi-hop** — require evidence from ≥2 sessions, scattered in position; label the required evidence hops. [#4]\n4. **Embed facts indirectly** — never state the answer; require inference. [#3]\n5. **Include knowledge-update items** — a stored answer must be superseded by a later fact (recall would *fail* this). [#6]\n6. **Include false-premise/abstention items** — correct behavior is refusal; tests against confident pattern-matching. [#7]\n7. **Mix explicit + colloquial temporal cues** to defeat similarity retrieval. [#5]\n8. **Report retrieval and end-to-end QA separately** — the gap is the reasoning signal; never compare recall@k to QA accuracy. [#15]\n9. **Sanity-check with a trivial baseline** (filesystem/dump-all) — if it matches your system, the benchmark isn't isolating memory. [#14]\n10. **Validate gold answers and avoid top_k ≥ corpus size**, which bypasses retrieval entirely. [#10, #11]\n11. **Semantic (not just string) dedup** against the training corpus to catch paraphrase leakage. [#21]\n\nNote: the strongest *positive* design rules come from the LongMemEval papers (arXiv, high reliability). The strongest *critiques* of LoCoMo come from a benchmarking-dispute GitHub thread (MemPalace issue #29 / discussion #747) and Letta's vendor blog — concrete and number-backed, but adversarial in origin, so treat the specific accusations as Medium-High rather than definitive."}],"resolvedModel":"claude-opus-4-8","totalDurationMs":157429,"totalTokens":35495,"totalToolUseCount":17,"usage":{"input_tokens":323,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1733,"cache_read_input_tokens":28494,"output_tokens":4945,"server_tool_use":{"web_search_requests":0,"web_fetch_requests":0},"service_tier":"standard","cache_creation":{"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1733},"inference_geo":"not_available","iterations":[{"input_tokens":323,"output_tokens":4945,"cache_read_input_tokens":28494,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1733,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":1733,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"type":"message"}],"speed":"standard"},"toolStats":{"readCount":0,"searchCount":0,"bashCount":0,"editFileCount":0,"linesAdded":0,"linesRemoved":0,"otherToolCount":17}},"sourceToolAssistantUUID":"86e95bd6-0df9-4078-b8dd-1f12b948462a","userType":"external","entrypoint":"cli","cwd":"/Users/gg/Work/Yogi","sessionId":"d8d6b712-ec33-4776-a194-d9a72216a25f","version":"2.1.183","gitBranch":"main"}
{"parentUuid":"dd6e182a-7eac-44bd-9e68-286af6ef981a","isSidechain":true,"promptId":"e117d56d-29de-4df3-8e3a-07358c407d0d","agentId":"a7ac81ca118e1dc58","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01XyMQ3DuQthVxrmzmhcanMq","type":"tool_result","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive evidence across all three layers. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n## Findings: Relative leverage of self-improvement layers for a local 8B build\n\n### Layer (a) — Skills / experiential memory (in-context, test-time learning)\n\n**Highest gain per unit of engineering, and the gains are large and immediate. No weight updates, no GPU, no training loop.**\n\n- **Dynamic Cheatsheet (test-time learning with adaptive memory, no weight changes):** GPT-4o on Game-of-24 went from ~10% → 99% by discovering and *reusing* a validated Python solution; arithmetic/equation-balancing tasks went from ~50% baseline to near-perfect by recalling previously-validated code; Claude 3.5 Sonnet roughly *doubled* AIME accuracy and gained +9% on GPQA-Diamond and +8% on MMLU-Pro Engineering/Physics — purely by curating reusable strategies in an external memory. This is the single best demonstration that a *retrieve-and-reuse skill/memory layer* compounds without touching weights. Source: https://arxiv.org/abs/2504.07952 (peer-reviewed, EACL 2026: https://aclanthology.org/2026.eacl-long.333/). Reliability: high (published, multiple models, large effect sizes — though the headline numbers are on frontier models, not 8B specifically).\n- **Controlled study (in-context vs fine-tuning generalization):** ICL \"generalizes more flexibly than fine-tuning\" — on the reversal-curse holdout, ICL hit near-ceiling while standard fine-tuning was near-zero. Key compounding insight: use ICL to *generate augmented training data* that later feeds fine-tuning, which then matches or beats ICL. Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2505.00661v1. Reliability: high (controlled experiments).\n- **Self-improving-agent line (Reflexion, Voyager, ExpeL):** agents learn from past failures by appending reflections / storing skills-as-code in a vector DB and retrieving at test time — \"essentially in-context learning,\" no weight updates. A critical caveat: retrieval generalizes only by *similarity to stored cases*, whereas weight-based memory generalizes by abstract rule to unseen inputs — so memory has a ceiling that distillation eventually breaks through. Sources: https://arxiv.org/html/2510.13220, https://arxiv.org/html/2604.27707. Reliability: medium-high (established methods + one critical-perspective paper).\n\n**Caveat for small models:** ICL is weaker on small models. The fair-comparison study (125M–30B) found ICL and fine-tuning \"generalize similarly\" with large variance, and that an 8B-class model is *not* an efficient in-context learner — fine-tuning can beat ICL on some tasks at this size. So for an 8B local build, the skills/memory layer still wins on *engineering-cost-per-gain*, but its raw ceiling is lower than it would be on a frontier model. Sources: https://aclanthology.org/2023.findings-acl.779/ (arXiv https://arxiv.org/abs/2305.16938). Reliability: high.\n\n### Layer (b) — Routing / cascade / navigator\n\n**Strong, well-quantified leverage — but it's primarily a cost/quality lever, and its value depends on having ≥2 capability tiers to route between.** For a single-model local build the \"model cascade\" framing partly degenerates (you only have qwen3:8b + Claude-Code-as-teacher), but the *navigator* idea — picking which sub-policy/context/skill to load — maps directly onto the memory layer above.\n\n- **RouteLLM:** maintain ~95% of frontier quality while routing ~85% of queries to cheaper models → 45–85% cost reduction. On GSM8K, 95% of GPT-4 performance using GPT-4 for only 14% of queries. Sources: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.18665, https://tianpan.co/blog/2025-11-03-llm-routing-model-cascades. Reliability: high (primary paper) / medium (blog synthesis).\n- **FrugalGPT (cascade):** cost-ordered chain with a cheap DistilBERT correctness-classifier that escalates only when confidence is low. Caveat: cascades add latency from multiple sequential calls; pure routing (single call) does not. Source: https://arxiv.org/pdf/2406.18665 and the cascade survey https://arxiv.org/pdf/2410.10347v3. Reliability: high.\n- **Recommended engineering order (from practitioner synthesis):** semantic caching → intent routing → confidence cascading → fallback chains; production frameworks (LiteLLM, RouteLLM, vLLM semantic router) cut custom dev. One early-abstention result: −13% cost and −5% error for +4.1% abstention. Source: https://tianpan.co/blog/2025-11-03-llm-routing-model-cascades. Reliability: medium.\n\n### Layer (c) — Distillation (fine-tuning a small student on traces)\n\n**Highest ceiling and the only layer that improves the *weights* (generalizes to unseen inputs), but the highest engineering + compute cost and the smallest gain-per-effort — wire it last.**\n\n- **Distilling Llama-3.1 8B → 1B (torchtune, single A100 80GB):** KD beat the baseline student by only ~+1–2% (HellaSwag +1.5%, TruthfulQA-acc +1.9%) and barely edged plain SFT (22.2 vs 22.1 on TruthfulQA-mc2). Crucially: **fine-tune the teacher on the target data *before* distilling.** Source: https://pytorch.org/blog/llama-into-torchtune/. Reliability: high (official PyTorch, exact numbers) — note gains are modest at the 1B scale and require a real GPU, not a 16GB Mac.\n- **Narrow-domain distillation closes the gap:** general benchmarks leave an 8B student ~3–8 pts below a 70B teacher, but on the *specific task you distilled for*, the gap often drops to <2%. 7B students distilled from 33k DeepSeek-R1 traces (Table-R1-SFT) show large in-domain and OOD accuracy gains. Sources: https://www.spheron.network/blog/model-distillation-gpu-cloud-7b-student-70b-teacher/ (vendor blog, treat as indicative), https://arxiv.org/pdf/2504.20946. Reliability: medium (vendor) / high (paper).\n- **Prompt-opt + fine-tuning together beats either alone:** optimizing prompts and weights jointly beat weights-only by up to **65%** and prompts-only by up to ~5% on multi-hop QA / math / classification across Mistral-7B, Llama-2-7B, Llama-3-8B. Best ordering was *prompt → fine-tune → prompt* (no single universal winner). This is direct 7–8B evidence that the layers are **complementary, not substitutes** — and that you should have the prompt/skill layer working *before* you fine-tune. Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2407.10930v1. Reliability: high (controlled, 7–8B models).\n\n### Framing layer — Compound AI systems (Berkeley / DSPy)\n\n- **Berkeley BAIR:** system design beats scaling for ROI — their canonical example: tripling training budget moves coding-contest solve-rate 30%→35%, but a *system* that samples-and-filters moves it 30%→80%. AlphaCode 2 (sample 1M, filter), Medprompt (retrieval + ensemble, beats specialized medical models), Gemini CoT@32 (90.04% MMLU vs GPT-4's 86.4%). Key line: \"iterating on a system design is often much faster than waiting for training runs.\" Source: https://bair.berkeley.edu/blog/2024/02/18/compound-ai-systems/. Reliability: high (authoritative, widely cited).\n- **DSPy:** automated prompt/pipeline optimization (MIPROv2) gives measurable lift with no weight changes, far cheaper than fine-tuning; recommended path is few-shot → MIPROv2 → fine-tune only if drift/traffic demands. Source: https://arxiv.org/html/2412.15298v1 and the joint-optimization paper above. Reliability: high.\n\n---\n\n## Ordering recommendation for a local 8B build (qwen3:8b, 16GB)\n\n1. **Skills / experiential memory FIRST (a).** Best gain-per-engineering-hour, no GPU, no training, runs entirely within the 16GB budget (memory is just embedding + retrieval via nomic-embed-text). The Dynamic Cheatsheet / Reflexion / ExpeL evidence shows large compounding gains from retrieve-and-reuse, and it generates the *traces* that layers (b) and (c) later consume. This is also the only layer with zero inference-budget risk.\n\n2. **Navigator / routing SECOND (b).** Cheap to add once memory exists — the navigator decides *which skill/context/sub-policy* to load (this is the form routing takes when you have one local model + a frontier teacher rather than a cost-ordered model fleet). Quantified 45–85% cost wins, and confidence-based escalation to the Claude-Code teacher tier is your natural cascade. Mostly classifier/threshold engineering, no training.\n\n3. **Distillation LAST (c).** Highest ceiling and the only weight-level generalization (breaks the similarity-retrieval ceiling of memory), but highest cost: it needs a real GPU (the torchtune case used an A100; 8B fine-tuning won't fit comfortably in 16GB unified memory — this matches the project's M3 note to \"pick a student small enough\"), and gains-per-effort are smallest. Critically, the 7–8B evidence says distillation pays off most (a) on narrow domains, (b) after the teacher is fine-tuned on the target data, and (c) *after* the prompt/skill layer is already optimized (prompt→fine-tune→prompt). So memory and routing aren't just earlier — they make distillation work better when you do reach it.\n\n**One load-bearing caveat for the 8B size specifically:** ICL/memory is a weaker learner at 8B than at frontier scale, so the memory layer's ceiling is lower than the headline frontier-model numbers suggest — but it remains the correct first move because every later layer (routing data, distillation traces, augmented fine-tuning sets) is bootstrapped from it."},{"type":"text","text":"agentId: ae758cc42afc8818b (use SendMessage with to: 'ae758cc42afc8818b' to continue this agent)\n<usage>subagent_tokens: 31709\ntool_uses: 15\nduration_ms: 146474</usage>"}]}]},"uuid":"f2747ebe-4d04-4109-b489-4c9bea4e9873","timestamp":"2026-06-21T05:16:27.745Z","toolUseResult":{"status":"completed","prompt":"You are a web research agent. Use WebSearch and WebFetch tools (load them first via ToolSearch with query \"select:WebSearch,WebFetch\"). Research this angle and return findings with cited URLs.\n\nANGLE: Relative leverage of self-improvement / compounding layers for a small LOCAL LLM build (single 8B model, 16GB RAM, e.g. qwen3:8b via Ollama). The layers in question: (a) skills / experiential memory, (b) routing / model-cascade / navigator (picking which sub-policy or context to use), (c) distillation (fine-tuning a small student on traces). Which gives the most measurable gain per unit of engineering for a local build, and in what order should they be wired? Look for:\n- Evidence on test-time / in-context learning (skills, memory) vs fine-tuning gains for small models.\n- LLM routing / cascade effectiveness and cost-quality tradeoffs.\n- Distillation gains for small (7-8B) student models and the cost of doing it locally.\n- Any \"compound AI systems\" framing (Berkeley AI blog, DSPy) on where leverage lies.\n\nSearch queries to try: \"compound AI systems Berkeley blog\", \"LLM routing cascade cost quality\", \"in-context learning vs fine-tuning small models\", \"distillation 7B student model gains\", \"self-improving agent in-context vs weight update\", \"DSPy optimization vs fine-tuning\".\n\nDo 6-10 searches, fetch 5-7 relevant pages. Extract concrete claims and numbers about relative leverage. Return findings only as your final message, each with claim + source URL + reliability note. Be concrete about ordering recommendation for a local 8B build.","agentId":"ae758cc42afc8818b","agentType":"general-purpose","content":[{"type":"text","text":"I have comprehensive evidence across all three layers. Here are my findings.\n\n---\n\n## Findings: Relative leverage of self-improvement layers for a local 8B build\n\n### Layer (a) — Skills / experiential memory (in-context, test-time learning)\n\n**Highest gain per unit of engineering, and the gains are large and immediate. No weight updates, no GPU, no training loop.**\n\n- **Dynamic Cheatsheet (test-time